üìñ The Story of Mimram

The Mimram flows through the Upper Lea (Hertfordshire) catchment, where our eDNA survey sampled 10 sites along its length. Analysis of water samples revealed a rich invertebrate community with 5,777 distinct genetic sequences (ESVs) representing 639 identified species and 228 families.

Compared to other chalk streams surveyed, the Mimram shows above average for diversity, ranking #4 of 10 rivers. The river supports 14 families of mayflies, stoneflies, and caddisflies (EPT) - key indicators of water quality.

Notable findings include the detection of conservation priority species (Water vole, Water shrew) and invasive species requiring management attention.
